a. Immediately record all collections on hand as of year-end in the appropriate fund accounts, particularly under the Cash – Local Treasury account, to reflect accurate balances in the financial statements;
b. Ensure strict compliance with the proper cut-off procedures for recording collections and deposits, especially those received close to year-end, to avoid misstatements in the financial reports; and
c. Strengthen coordination between the Accounting and Treasury Offices to ensure timely submission and recording of the Report of Collections and Deposits and other related documents.

a. Regularly review and validate system-generated depreciation schedules to ensure the accuracy and completeness of depreciation computations. This includes verifying that encoded data complies with the requirements of IPSAS 17 and other applicable accounting standards and policies;
b. Perform manual depreciation computation of the PPEs as a control mechanism to verify the accuracy of system-generated figures and as a guide for necessary accounting entry adjustments. For PPE items where depreciation was delayed, manual calculations should be performed using the actual acquisition or completion date as the basis for depreciation, rather than the date of recording in the books;
c. Review and clean up the PPE register, ensuring fully depreciated assets are not being depreciated further and that all capitalized items are included; and
d. Prepare and record the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the understatement of depreciation and accumulated depreciation accounts, and to ensure that the carrying amounts of PPE are fairly stated in accordance with applicable accounting principles.

a. Reclassify all semi-expendable items with acquisition costs below ₱50,000.00 that are still recorded under PPE and were still not issued to the end-user to the appropriate inventory/semi-expendable property accounts; 
b. Record the necessary adjustments to the Government Equity account as part of the beginning balance adjustment, as mandated under COA Circular No. 2022-004;
c. The Municipal Accounting Office ensure the proper recording of all purchases and issuances of semi-expendable property under the appropriate semi-expendable inventory and expense accounts, in accordance with COA Circular Nos. 2022-004 and 2024-006;
d. The Municipal Accounting Office and the GSO maintain the prescribed inventory records, including the Semi-Expendable Property Ledger Card, Registry of Semi-Expendable Property Issued, and related reports, to enhance property monitoring and control; and
e. The General Services Office update the Report on the Physical Count of PPE, ensuring alignment with current accounting policies.

a. Direct the concerned departments or implementing units to expedite the implementation of the related programs or projects, and ensure the preparation and submission of liquidation reports, along with the necessary supporting documents, to the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO);
b. Instruct the MAO to initiate the necessary journal entries and adjustments, if applicable, and to ensure that complete details of the concerned fund transfers are properly reflected in the respective subsidiary ledgers;
