Recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed on the following:
The Municipal Accountant to provide adjusting entries to reclassify the unliquidated cash advance for confidential expenses to its appropriate G/L account and furnish the Office of the Auditor a copy of its Journal Entry Voucher (JEV);
Locate any liquidation reports and other supporting documents pertaining to the unliquidated cash advance for confidential funds to ascertain whether these have been submitted to the COA-ICFAU, supported with a duly received transmittal letter, and effect its liquidation thereof if these records are retrieved;
The Management require all officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances immediately and institute appropriate legal sanction against concerned officials or employees, by withholding or suspension of their salaries; and
For dormant unliquidated cash advances as thoroughly determined by the Office of the Municipal Accountant, follow the procedures and guidelines prescribed in COA Circular No. 2023-008 on its proper disposition/write-off with consideration of the effectivity which is for a period of one year.

Recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to require:
The Inventory Committee to conduct semestral physical count of inventories and submit the result of the physical count using the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Office of the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
The General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the stock cards for each supply/inventory item and periodically reconcile the same with the accounting records and the result of the physical count;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC) for each supply/inventory item and periodically reconcile the same with the supply records and the result of the physical count, as well as provide the appropriate disclosures in the notes to financial statements pursuant to Paragraph 47 of IPSAS 12 including, but not limited to, the amount of inventory recognized as expenses during the year; and
The Municipal Accountant to strictly follow the Perpetual Inventory Method by recording first the purchases of supplies and materials in the appropriate inventory accounts, and recognizing the corresponding expenses only upon issuances/distribution to the end-users.

(a) conduct a thorough investigation into the unauthorized check withdrawals; 

